      <h3>1. Understanding the Science of a Calorie Deficit</h3>
      <p>
        A calorie deficit occurs when you consistently ingest fewer calories than your body expends. This gap forces your 
        body to tap into stored energy reserves—mainly fat, but sometimes glycogen or muscle tissue—leading to weight loss. 
        Over time, this principle has proven effective for shedding excess weight. Still, it is essential to do it 
        systematically and sustainably, considering factors such as protein intake, healthy fats, and carbohydrates.
      </p>
      <p>
        Many ask: “<em>Does calorie deficit truly guarantee weight loss</em>?” As long as you remain in a negative energy 
        balance, you will typically see a downward shift in body mass. The majority of professionals across the fitness 
        industry—from personal trainers to registered dietitians—acknowledge a deficit as a primary mechanism for fat loss. 
        However, nuances exist, especially if you have hormonal imbalances, medical conditions (like hypothyroidism), or 
        are on specific dietary regimens such as “<em>calorie deficit keto</em>” or “<em>calorie deficit plus intermittent 
        fasting</em>.”
      </p>

      <h3>2. Balancing Macros in a Calorie Deficit</h3>
