        high protein</em>,” it’s clear that macros matter. A well-thought-out ratio of carbs, proteins, and fats is not 
        just about losing weight, but losing the right kind of weight: primarily fat rather than muscle. Proteins aid in 
        muscle preservation, carbohydrates fuel workouts, and healthy fats support hormonal functions. 
      </p>
      <p>
        The typical recommendation in many “<em>calorie deficit and high protein</em>” discussions is ensuring about 
        25-40% of your total daily intake derives from protein. If your daily target is 2,000 calories, for instance, 
        30% protein translates to 600 calories from protein, or 150g of protein (since 1g of protein = 4 calories). 
        Adjust these ratios slightly based on your unique goals—like muscle gain or a stricter fat-loss approach.
      </p>

