      <p>
        When we mention “<em>calorie deficit calculator</em>” or “<em>calorie deficit calculator with exercise</em>,” 
        the concept of TDEE (Total Daily Energy Expenditure) becomes vital. TDEE combines BMR (the energy used for bodily 
        functions at rest) with the additional calorie burn from activities like walking, running, weight-lifting, or 
        sports. Adjusting your TDEE can be done either by changing your activity level or by verifying your base BMR. 
        Common search queries like “<em>calorie deficit calculator bmr</em>” or “<em>calorie deficit calculator exercise 
        included</em>” highlight how important it is to reflect your real energy output in the calculations.
      </p>
      <p>
